<div class="entry hentry" id="entry-75264">
<!-- date published -->
<span class="timestamp published" title="2010-07-30T06:00:58+00:00">
<span class="date">July 30, 2010, <em>6:00 am</em></span></span>
<!-- date updated -->
<!-- <abbr class="updated" title="2010-07-30T08:19:52+00:00">&#8212; Updated: 8:19 am</abbr> -->
<!-- Title -->
<h1 class="entry-title">Are We a Nation of Property Owners?</h1>
<!-- Byline --><address class="byline author vcard">By <a href="/author/uwe-e-reinhardt/" class="url fn" title="See all posts by UWE E. REINHARDT">UWE E. REINHARDT</a></address><!-- The Content -->
<div class="entry-content"><div class="w75 left"><img src="http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/blogs_v3/economix/todays-economist.png" alt="Today's Economist" /></div>
<p><em><a id="aptureLink_sjBQhVI1vx" href="http://www.nytimes.com/ref/business/economy/reinhardt.ready.html">Uwe E. Reinhardt</a> is an economics professor at Princeton.<br />
</em></p>
<p>In a thought-provoking essay, “<a href="http://www.american.com/archive/2010/july/the-return-of-the-jeffersonian-vision-and-the-rejection-of-progressivism">The Return of the Jeffersonian Vision and the Rejection of Progressivism</a>,” Michael Barone, a resident fellow of the <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about the American Enterprise Institute for Public Policy Research." href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/a/american_enterprise_institute_for_public_policy_research/index.html?inline=nyt-org">American Enterprise Institute</a> and a prominent commentator in the media, argues that there is currently under way among voters a shift away from the redistributionist policies of progressives toward America’s traditional “culture of independence, a culture as old as the republic itself.”</p>
<p>As an economist, I am not qualified to discourse on Mr. Barone’s hypothesis, learning instead at the feet of my distinguished colleagues in Princeton’s Department of Politics, among them Larry Bartels, whose <a href="http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&amp;aid=286248">research</a> and <a href="http://www.princeton.edu/%7Ebartels/kansasqjps06.pdf">writings</a> are focused on such matters.</p>
<p>What caught this economist’s eye, however, was this assertion in Mr. Barone’s essay (to which I have added italics):</p>
<p>&#8220;The fact is that we are once again, as in the days of the early republic and not in the heyday of the Progressives and the New Dealers, <em>a republic of property owners</em>. Most Americans have accumulated &#8212; or will, during the course of their working years, accumulate &#8212; <em>significant</em> amounts of wealth. And that is why, I believe, American voters seem to be rejecting the policies of the Obama Democrats.”<br />
<span id="more-75264"></span><br />
It would be great for future fiscal policy if, indeed, most Americans accumulated &#8212; or will, during the course of their working years accumulate &#8212; significant amounts of wealth. But data on <a href="http://www.nasi.org/usr_doc/SS_Brief_025.pdf">the sources of income of Americans in retirement</a> suggest otherwise.</p>
<p><strong>Shares of Income From Specified Sources by Income Quintile, 2004</strong> (Married Couples and Unmarried Persons Age 65 and Older)</p>
<div class="w480"><img id="100000000299392" src="http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/07/30/business/30economist-reinhardt1/30economist-reinhardt1-blogSpan.jpg" alt="" /><span class="credit">Virginia P. Reno and Joni Lavery, “Social Security and Retirement Income Adequacy,” National Academy of Social insurance, Social Security Brief No.25, May, 2007: Figure 4.</span></div>
<p>As the chart shows, Social Security payments by government appear to constitute by far the most important source of retirement income for more than half of elderly Americans, who also rely heavily on tax-financed Medicare &#8212; and frequently Medicaid as well &#8212; for their personal health care. Income from owned assets plays only a minor role for most retired Americans. Their heavy reliance on government-financed retirement benefits hardly suggests a “culture of independence.”</p>
<p>My doubts on the “republic of property owners” are raised further upon contemplating data on the distribution of income and wealth in the United States.</p>
<p>The chart below, taken from an exhaustive <a href="http://www.federalreserve.gov/pubs/feds/2009/200913/200913pap.pdf">study</a> by Arthur Kennickell of the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve, presents a so-called Lorenz curve on the distribution of family income and net worth for married couples and unmarried people 65 and older in the United States. “Net worth” is the value of real or financial assets owned by households or individuals, minus debt they owe.</p>
<div class="w533"><img src="http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/07/29/business/economy/economix-30reinhardtchart/economix-30reinhardtchart-custom1.jpg" alt="DESCRIPTION" /><span class="credit"></span> <span class="caption">Arthur B. Kennickell, Chief, Microeconomic Surveys Section, Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, “Ponds and Streams: Wealth and Income in the U.S. 1989 to 2007” (January 7, 2009),&#8221; January 7, 2009.</span></div>
<p>A Lorenz curve is an analytic tool widely used in economics to represent the distribution of some variable of interest (e.g., income, wealth or health spending) among members of a population that  is arrayed, on the horizontal axis, in ascending values of either income or wealth. (More on this can be learned from <a href="http://www.princeton.edu/~reinhard/pdfs/597-F2009LORENZ-CURVES-AND-INEQUALITY-IN-HEALTH-CARE.pdf">this lecture</a> of mine.)</p>
<p>Consider, for example, the three narrowly clustered curves labeled “net worth.” For those curves, the population is represented on the horizontal axis in deciles, in increasing values of wealth owned. Thus, the deciles on the left of the horizontal axis represent families with less wealth, while the deciles to the right represent families with higher wealth.</p>
<p>If we pick, say, the number 80 on the horizontal axis and draw a vertical line above it until it cuts the curves labeled “net worth,” and if we then draw a horizontal line to the vertical axis on the left, it will mark about 15 percent to 16 percent on that axis. This means the bottom eight deciles of the population, arrayed from low to high in terms of wealth owned, own only about 15 percent to 16 percent of the national’s total household net worth, while the remaining wealthier 20 percent of the population own 85 percent or so of the nation’s total household net worth, and so on.</p>
<p>If we repeat the exercise, but draw the vertical line to the curves labeled “income,” we infer that the bottom eight deciles of the population, arrayed from low to higher incomes, receive roughly 38 percent or so of total income, while the remaining 20 percent receive slightly more than over 60 percent.</p>
<p>Thus, it appears that total income in the nation is quite unevenly distributed, but not nearly as much as is the net worth of households.</p>
<p>In the chart below, taken from other authoritative sources, the data exhibit the same pattern. These data <a href="http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_589.pdf">have been configured</a> by Edward N. Wolff, a professor at <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about New York University." href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/n/new_york_university/index.html?inline=nyt-org">New York University</a>, senior scholar at the <a href="http://www.levyinstitute.org/">Levy Economics Institute</a> of <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Bard College" href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/b/bard_college/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Bard College</a> and a much-cited authority on the distribution of income and wealth in the United States.</p>
<p>For each category &#8212; net worth excluding home, net worth including home, and income &#8212; Professor Wolff ranks households from high to low and then shows what fraction of national net worth or income is held by the top 1 percent, 10 percent, 20 percent and bottom 40 percent of households. The data on income are for 2006, those for net worth for 2007. In this chart, Professor Wolff also shows how these distributions have changed over time since 1983.</p>
<p>The chart shows that close to half of the American population does not have any net worth to speak of. Ideally, of course, one would like to have a similar table for the population 65 or older. Even so, in conjunction with the first chart in this post, the data make it safe to conjecture that a large fraction of Americans enter retirement heavily dependent on government for their daily sustenance and health care.</p>
<div class="w480"><img id="100000000299755" src="http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/07/30/business/30economist-reinhardt4/30economist-reinhardt4-blogSpan.jpg" alt="" /><span class="credit">Edward N. Wolff, “Recent Trends in Household Wealth in the United States,” Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, Working Paper No. 589, March 2010, Table 2.</span></div>
<p>At the end of his paper, Professor Wolff presents many different and fascinating data displays. His Table 1, for example, shows that 18.6 percent of the United States population in 2007 had a zero or negative net worth and 30 percent had a net worth of less than $10,000 &#8212; and “net worth” here includes home ownership.</p>
<p>His Table 9, “The Percent of Total Assets Held by Wealth Class, 2007,” indicates that in 2007 the wealthiest 10 percent of the population owned 89.4 percent of the total value of “stocks and mutual funds” in the United States and, in general, 80 percent or more of other financial or real non-home investment assets and about half of the total value of principal residences, deposits, life insurance and pensions.</p>
<p>It is said that beauty lies in the eyes of the beholder. So, evidently, does the interpretation of economic data.</p>
<p>Michael Barone may see in the charts published here “a republic of property owners.” I do not.</p>
<p>Instead I see a people with a very short horizon over which they appear to measure their cherished “independence from government” &#8212; the years when they are younger and healthy and have a good job, ideally one that provides them with good health insurance.</p>
<p>As they grow older and sicker, however, very large cohorts of Americans <a href="http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/surveys/2009_Archives/PPP_Release_National_819513.pdf">have come and in the future will come</a> to look to the rest of society &#8212; that is, government &#8212; for their main source of income maintenance and health care financing, even as <a href="http://www.weeklystandard.com/weblogs/TWSFP/2009/08/hands_off_my_medicare_1.asp">they may protest</a>, at political rallies, that they want “government out of their Medicare.”</p>
<p>For millions of retired Americans, the bill for only one serious hospital episode would wipe out whatever lifetime accumulated net worth they have.</p>
<p>Life-cycle independence from government may be part of the American Dream, but it is just that &#8212; a dream. In the end, when the going gets tough, the tough in this country tend to run to the government &#8212; even the self-styled rugged individualists.</p>
</div><!-- end .entry-content -->
</div><div class="entry-meta">
